item.title: Restore Our Shores
item.description:
Restore Our Shores

According to the Brevard Zoo, oysters are a keystone species for the Indian River Lagoon. Unfortunately, oyster populations are decreasing from various causes like climate change-induced ocean acidification. To combat the decline, we will be bagging shells for the oyster reef with the Restore Our Shores initiative.

We will send out more details and the location for people attending as February 5th draws closer. We hope to see you there!

Photo Credit: Brevard Zoo/Restore Our Shores

From Saturday, February 5, 2022 8:00 AM to 12:00 PM EST at TBA.

item.title: CPFIT Training - Graph Theory: Spanning Trees and Shortest Paths
item.description:
CPFIT Training - Graph Theory: Spanning Trees and Shortest Paths

This will be one of CPFIT's biweekly training meetings, where we help teach students how to effectively competitively program. During this meeting, we discuss how to find minimum spanning trees and how to find the shortest path between points in a graph. We highly recommend this meeting to everyone interested in competitive programming or computer science.

From Saturday, February 12, 2022 1:00 PM to 4:00 PM EST at OEC 130.
